Skyline Innovations, for Cost-effective Glazed Polymeric Solar Water Heating Systems. This innovative, low-cost technology was installed at one Multi-family Housing application, then compared to the more conventional flat plate and evacuated tube technologies at two other Multi-family Housing applications.

Standard Solar, for the States First Solar Microgrid at a mixed-use property owned by Konterra, near Laurel. This project involved an islandable microgrid at the Konterra property, energized by a solar PV array kept online by advanced energy storage system in the event of a conventional power grid outage. Most solar PV systems are knocked offline by a power grid outage since inverters require energy to convert PV power, in DC, to usable power, in AC. Several end-users could benefit from such a system, including first responders, the military, telecommunications, waste water treatment plants, and emergency shelters.

TimberRock Energy Solutions, for Solar-Charged Electric Vehicles (EVs) at a General Motors Plant in White Marsh.This innovative configuration allows a solar PV array, Lithium-ion batteries, and advanced inverters to channel energy to send solar electrons to EVs, the GM plant, or the power grid for Frequency Regulation ancillary services which could help pay for the batteries. This project will also be, perhaps, the worlds first real Vehicle-to-Grid analysis that uses four on-the-road electric vehicles made by a major auto manufacturer.

Alice Ferguson Foundation Geothermal Heating & Cooling for the LIving Building Challenge at the Potomac Watershed Study Center at Hard Bargain Farm in Accokeek.The Alice Ferguson Foundation will utilize geothermal heating & cooling as a major contributor to LEED, Living Building Challenge, and Net Zero Energy Building energy sustainability frameworks. This project could lead to the validation for the Maryland to develop greenhouse gas reducing codes and standards that include geothermal heating & cooling. The grant will provide assistance with the design and engineering costs associated with holistic system design that will allow a set of buildings to generate more energy than it consumers on an annual basis.

Project Name: Geothermal Heating & Cooling for Living Building Challenge
Notes: Kentlands Citizens Assembly Installation of a Standing Column of Water (SWC) Geothermal Heating & Cooling System at Kentlands Community Center in Gaithersburg.This Game Changer Grant helped to install a standing column water (SCW) geothermal system that are up to 2 times more efficient than traditional closed loop wells. This development could lead to the conversion of thousands of existing water wells to multi-purpose drinking/GHC wells across the region. The grant mitigates high upfront costs associated with uniqueness of this type of retrofit system.
